---
import ResourcePage from '@layouts/ResourcePage.astro';
import { RESOURCE_CATEGORIES } from '@data/resources';

const category = RESOURCE_CATEGORIES.find((c) => c.slug === 'septic-installation-replacement')!;
---

<ResourcePage
  category={category}
  title="Septic Installation & Replacement Guides | Cumberland Septic Hub"
>
  <h2>When Installation Becomes the Conversation</h2>
  <p>
    Septic installation projects arrive from two directions. New construction needs a system
    where none exists — the common case across rural Upper Cumberland, where sewer lines stop at
    the town's edge. Replacement projects retire a system that evaluation has shown to be beyond
    practical repair: an exhausted drain field, a structurally failing tank, or components whose
    fixes no longer hold. Home additions and property-use changes sit between the two — extra
    bedrooms, an accessory dwelling or a converted building can change what a system must handle,
    which can mean expansion or replacement even when nothing is broken.
  </p>

  <h2>The General Shape of a Project</h2>
  <p>
    Every property and jurisdiction differs, and requirements change — so treat this as the
    general sequence most projects recognize, not as instructions for any specific property:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Property and project information.</strong> Lot size and layout, water source,
      planned structure, bedroom count and intended use.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Site and soil-related evaluation where required.</strong> Soil and site conditions
      largely determine what kind of system can go where — this step shapes everything after it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>System planning.</strong> Design, sizing and placement that fit the evaluation and
      the project.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Applicable permits or approvals.</strong> Confirmed with the appropriate Tennessee
      or county authority for the specific property and project.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Contractor selection.</strong> Scope, timeline, site handling and terms — settled
      before equipment arrives.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Installation.</strong> Excavation, tank setting and field construction, paced by
      weather and access.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Inspection or approval where applicable.</strong> Whatever verification the
      jurisdiction requires.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Final grading and restoration.</strong> The surface put back as agreed with the
      contractor.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>New Construction Versus Replacement</h2>
  <p>
    New builds have the advantage of sequencing — the system is planned alongside the house, and
    the site can be chosen with the field in mind. Replacements inherit constraints: the old
    system occupies ground, an exhausted field may rule out its own footprint, and the household
    usually needs wastewater service to continue during the work. Replacement fields often land
    on a different part of the property than the original — one of many reasons the site
    evaluation, not the old system's location, drives the plan.
  </p>

  <h2>Access and Site Realities</h2>
  <p>
    Installation is excavation work. Equipment needs a way in; trees, slopes, utilities and
    property lines all shape the layout; and saturated ground can pause a project. On plateau and
    lake terrain — common across this region — access questions deserve early answers, a topic
    the <a href="/resources/upper-cumberland-septic-guide/">Upper Cumberland septic guide</a>
    covers in regional detail.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions Worth Settling Before Ground Breaks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>What did the site evaluation find, and how does the design respond to it?</li>
    <li>What approvals apply to this property and project, and who obtains them?</li>
    <li>How will equipment reach the site, and what surface impact is expected?</li>
    <li>What does the timeline depend on — weather, inspections, materials?</li>
    <li>What restoration is included when the work is done?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    One caution that repeats throughout this site because it matters: no system type can be
    called appropriate for a property without a qualified evaluation of that property, and
    requirements vary by property, project and jurisdiction. Confirm current requirements with
    the provider and the appropriate authority rather than building plans on general
    information — this page included.
  </p>

  <h2>Starting a Project Conversation</h2>
  <p>
    Describe the project stage (planning, building, replacing), the property, what is known about
    any existing system, and your timeline.
    <a href="/septic-installation-cookeville-tn/">Request installation information</a> and the
    project can be connected with an independent local installation professional who works from
    the property, not the brochure.
  </p>
</ResourcePage>
